WASHINGTON (AP) — Two energy companies bid a combined $315 million in an auction for the rights to produce power from wind energy in two areas off the coasts of North Carolina and South Carolina, the U.S. Department of the Interior said.The Bureau of Ocean Energy Management’s lease sale offered two lease areas covering 110,091 acres (44,500 hectares) in the Carolina Long Bay area, according to a news release from the department on Wednesday. If fully developed, the leases could result in about 1.3 gigawatts of offshore wind energy, enough to power about 500,000 homes. TotalEnergies Renewables USA, LLC paid a reported $160 million for 54,937 acres (22,232 hectares) off the coast. Duke Energy Renewables Wind, LLC bid $155 million for 55,154 acres (22,320 hectares), the release said. Specifically, the sites are 50 miles (80 km) east of Myrtle Beach, South Carolina, and about 30 miles (48 km) south of Bald Head Island in North Carolina.ADVERTISEMENTBefore the leases are finalized, the U.S. Department of Justice and Federal Trade Commission will conduct an anti-competitiveness review of the auction, and the provisional winners will be required to pay any balance on the winning bids and provide financial assurance to BOEM.BusinessCrypto comes to Washington. Will the millions buy influence?FIFA takes on EA Sports video game in soccer's new rivalrySlightly more Americans seek jobless aid last weekUS producer prices surge 11% in April as food prices jump The leases are part of President Joe Biden’s goal of increasing clean energy generation and providing the U.S. with more independent sources of power and lowering electricity bills for customers, the U.S. Department of the Interior said in a news release Friday.The Interior Department has already leased wind power sites off New York’s coast and is planning to add sites off California and Oregon, the Gulf of Maine, the Gulf of Mexico and in the central Atlantic Ocean, according to a statement earlier this year.